  <h2 class="entry-title">Rockefeller Center</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown, 48th–51st St</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic + Commercial</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">19 Art Deco commercial buildings on 22 acres, built through the Depression. The only large-scale privately owned urban complex in the US designated a National Historic Landmark. The sunken plaza and channel gardens between 5th and 6th Avenues constitute one of the great urban sequences in American architecture. The Top of the Rock observation deck (70th floor) offers the best elevated view of Central Park.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Rockefeller+Center,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ 45 Rockefeller Plaza</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="tower" data-hood="midtown" data-arch="van-alen">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Chrysler_Building"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Van Alen, William</span><span class="entry-cost">1930</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Chrysler Building</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown, 42nd St</span><span class="entry-tag">Tower</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">1,046 feet, 1930. Stainless steel eagle gargoyles at the 61st floor replicate Chrysler hood ornaments at 1:1 scale. The sunburst crown — seven radiating steel arches with triangular windows — was assembled in secret inside the building and hoisted in 90 minutes to surpass the Bank of Manhattan Tower. The tallest building in the world for 11 months until the Empire State Building. The lobby is one of the finest Art Deco interiors in the city.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=405+Lexington+Ave,+New+York,+NY+10174" target="_blank">↗ 405 Lexington Ave</a>
</div>



<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="mckim">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Grand_Central_Terminal"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Reed &amp; Stem + Warren &amp; Wetmore</span><span class="entry-cost">1913</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Grand Central Terminal</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Beaux-Arts. The Main Concourse — 275 feet long, 120 feet wide, 125 feet high — is one of the great interior civic spaces in the world. The celestial ceiling mural (2,500 stars, painted in reverse) by Charles Basing. Ramps rather than stairs connect the levels; 44 platforms on two underground levels. Free and open daily.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=89+E+42nd+St,+New+York,+NY+10017" target="_blank">↗ 89 E 42nd St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="tower" data-hood="midtown" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Chrysler_Building"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Van Allen, William</span><span class="entry-cost">1930</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Chrysler Building</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown</span><span class="entry-tag">Tower</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">77 stories, 1,046 feet. Art Deco. Seven stainless steel eagles project from the 61st floor corners — derived from Chrysler hood ornaments. The sunburst crown of 7 radiating arches, each pierced by triangular windows. For 11 months in 1930 the tallest building in the world. The lobby — red Moroccan marble floor, African marble walls — is open to the public.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=405+Lexington+Ave,+New+York,+NY+10174" target="_blank">↗ 405 Lexington Ave</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="museum" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="mckim">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="American_Museum_of_Natural_History"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Vaux, Calvert (orig. 1877) + Studio Gang (Gilder Center, 2023)</span><span class="entry-cost">1877–2023</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">American Museum of Natural History + Gilder Center</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Upper West Side</span><span class="entry-tag">Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">26 interconnected buildings across four city blocks. The Gilder Center (Studio Gang / Jeanne Gang, 2023): a five-story shotcrete atrium with cave-like undulating walls — no right angles, no formwork, blasted directly onto rebar. 33 new connections between buildings. The most architecturally significant new museum addition in NYC in a decade. $465M. The Rose Center's Hayden Sphere (Polshek Partnership, 2000) is also worth a pass through.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=200+Central+Park+West,+New+York,+NY+10024" target="_blank">↗ 200 Central Park West</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="The_Cloisters"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Collens, Charles (architect) + Rockefeller / Metropolitan Museum</span><span class="entry-cost">1938</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">The Cloisters</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Fort Tryon Park, Upper Manhattan</span><span class="entry-tag">Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">A branch of the Metropolitan Museum housing medieval European art and architecture. Five actual medieval cloisters — stone arcaded courtyards — were dismantled and shipped from France, Spain, and elsewhere and reassembled here above the Hudson. Rockefeller donated the land and purchased the Palisades across the river to preserve the view. The gardens are planted to medieval specifications.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=99+Margaret+Corbin+Dr,+New+York,+NY+10040" target="_blank">↗ Fort Tryon Park</a>
</div>

