  <h2 class="entry-title">New York Public Library — Schwarzman Building</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span><span class="icon icon-free">Free Entry</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown — Bryant Park</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Beaux-Arts marble, 1911. Patience and Fortitude — the marble lions by Edward Clark Potter — flank the Fifth Avenue steps. The Rose Main Reading Room on the third floor: 78 feet wide, 297 feet long, 52 feet high, with painted ceiling panels. Free and open daily. One of the most important interior rooms in New York.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=476+5th+Ave,+New+York,+NY+10018" target="_blank">↗ 476 5th Ave at 42nd St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic museum" data-hood="midtown" data-arch="mckim">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Morgan_Library_%26_Museum"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">McKim, Charles Follen (orig.) + Piano, Renzo (2006)</span><span class="entry-cost">1906 / 2006</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">The Morgan Library &amp; Museum</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Murray Hill, Midtown</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic + Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Originally the private library of J.P. Morgan. McKim's 1906 pink Tennessee marble building — a Roman palazzo with a polychrome rotunda and triple-tiered walnut bookcases accessed by hidden spiral staircases behind bookshelves. Renzo Piano's 2006 glass atrium connects three historic structures into a unified campus. The library itself is one of the most beautiful rooms in New York. Free Fridays 5–7pm.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=225+Madison+Ave,+New+York,+NY+10016" target="_blank">↗ 225 Madison Ave</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="museum" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="mckim">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Frick_Collection"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Carrère &amp; Hastings (1914) + Selldorf Architects (2024)</span><span class="entry-cost">1914 / reopened 2024</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">The Frick Collection</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Upper East Side</span><span class="entry-tag">Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Henry Clay Frick's Gilded Age mansion converted to a museum in 1935. Carrère &amp; Hastings, 1914. Selldorf Architects' 2024 renovation opened the bowling alley, music room, and garden court to the public for the first time — significantly expanding access to spaces previously closed for 90 years. One of the great intimate museum experiences in any city.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=1+E+70th+St,+New+York,+NY+10021" target="_blank">↗ 1 E 70th St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="museum" data-hood="brooklyn" data-arch="mckim">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Brooklyn_Museum"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">McKim Mead &amp; White</span><span class="entry-cost">1897</span></div>
