  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Prospect Heights, Brooklyn</span><span class="entry-tag">Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Beaux-Arts, 1897. Originally designed to be the largest museum in the world — only one wing of the intended plan was completed. 560,000 sq ft across five floors. Strong Egyptian, African, and feminist art collections. The grand Eastern Parkway entrance steps are a civic gathering place.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=200+Eastern+Pkwy,+Brooklyn,+NY+11238" target="_blank">↗ 200 Eastern Pkwy</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="brooklyn" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Brooklyn_Botanic_Garden"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted Brothers (landscape)</span><span class="entry-cost">1910</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Brooklyn Botanic Garden</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Prospect Heights, Brooklyn</span><span class="entry-tag">Garden</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">52 acres adjacent to Prospect Park. Japanese Hill-and-Pond Garden (1915) — one of the oldest Japanese gardens in the US outside Japan. Cherry esplanade (the Sakura Matsuri festival draws 50,000 in late April). Tropical, desert, and temperate glasshouses.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=990+Washington+Ave,+Brooklyn,+NY+11225" target="_blank">↗ 990 Washington Ave</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="New_York_Botanical_Garden"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted Brothers (landscape) + Thain Family Forest</span><span class="entry-cost">1891</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">New York Botanical Garden</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Bronx</span><span class="entry-tag">Garden</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">250 acres in the Bronx. The Thain Family Forest is 50 acres of old-growth New York forest — one of the largest remaining tracts of the forest that once covered all of NYC. The Enid A. Haupt Conservatory (1902) is a Victorian glass palace housing tropical and desert biomes. Metro-North from Grand Central, 20 minutes.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=2900+Southern+Blvd,+Bronx,+NY+10458" target="_blank">↗ 2900 Southern Blvd, Bronx</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park civic" data-hood="brooklyn" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Green-Wood_Cemetery"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Upjohn, Richard (Gothic Revival gate) + Almerin Hotchkiss (landscape)</span><span class="entry-cost">1838</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Green-Wood Cemetery</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-free">Free Entry</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Sunset Park, Brooklyn</span><span class="entry-tag">Park + Historic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">478 acres of glacial moraines in Brooklyn. Richard Upjohn's Gothic Revival brownstone entrance gate (1861) — a National Historic Landmark. One of the primary inspirations for Central Park: Olmsted and Vaux visited and adopted its naturalistic landscape principles. The highest point in Brooklyn, with views to Manhattan. Leonard Bernstein, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Boss Tweed, Horace Greeley buried here.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=500+25th+St,+Brooklyn,+NY+11232" target="_blank">↗ 500 25th St, Brooklyn</a>
</div>

<!-- ── PUBLIC SPACE + PARKS ── -->
<p class="section-label">Public Space + Parks</p>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="midtown uptown" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Central_Park"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted, Frederick Law + Vaux, Calvert</span><span class="entry-cost">1858–1876</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Central Park</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span><span class="icon icon-free">Free</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown to Upper Manhattan</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">843 acres, 59th to 110th Street. The Greensward Plan, submitted to an 1858 design competition, was the first large-scale designed public landscape in the United States. Olmsted and Vaux conceived the park as a democratic counter to the city grid — the 36 crossing roads pass below the park surface in sunken transverse cuts so pedestrians and traffic never meet. The Ramble, the Great Lawn, the Reservoir, Sheep Meadow, the Bethesda Fountain and Terrace, and Belvedere Castle are each distinct spatial episodes within a continuous designed landscape.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Central+Park,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Central Park</a>
</div>


<div class="entry" data-type="plaza" data-hood="hudson-yards" data-arch="dsr">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="High_Line_(New_York_City)"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Diller Scofidio + Renfro + James Corner FO</span><span class="entry-cost">2009</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">The High Line</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span><span class="icon icon-iconic">⊙ Iconic</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">West Chelsea → Hudson Yards</span><span class="entry-tag">Plaza + Infrastructure</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">1.45-mile elevated linear park on a disused 1930s freight rail viaduct. DS+R with James Corner Field Operations. Tracks embedded in plantings, original steel structure left legible. The most debated piece of urban infrastructure in 21st-century NYC.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=The+High+Line,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Gansevoort St Entry</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="roosevelt-island" data-arch="kahn">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Franklin_D._Roosevelt_Four_Freedoms_State_Park"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Kahn, Louis I.</span><span class="entry-cost">1974 / built 2012</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Four Freedoms Park</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Roosevelt Island</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Kahn's last project, completed posthumously from his original drawings. Triangular granite plaza at the southern tip of Roosevelt Island. Two rows of linden trees narrow toward a bust of FDR — axial compression from wide entry to single terminus.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Four+Freedoms+Park,+Roosevelt+Island" target="_blank">↗ Roosevelt Island South</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="plaza" data-hood="midtown" data-arch="snohetta">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Times_Square"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Snøhetta</span><span class="entry-cost">2016</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Times Square Pedestrian Plaza</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown</span><span class="entry-tag">Plaza + Infrastructure</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Granite pavers replacing former Broadway car lanes from 42nd to 47th Street. Foundational infrastructure in NYC's rethinking of car-to-pedestrian priority in the core.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Times+Square,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Broadway at 45th St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="west-village" data-arch="white">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Washington_Square_Park"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Stanford White (arch) + Olmsted Bros (landscape)</span><span class="entry-cost">1895</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Washington Square Park</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Greenwich Village</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">9.75 acres. Stanford White marble arch, 1892. Originally a potter's field; bodies encountered during 2021 renovations. The social and geographic center of lower Manhattan.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Washington+Square+Park,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Washington Square Park</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Riverside_Park_(Manhattan)"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted, Frederick Law + Vaux, Calvert</span><span class="entry-cost">1873</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Riverside Park</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Upper West Side</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Four miles along the Hudson, 72nd to 158th Street. The quieter counterpart to Central Park — narrower, river-facing throughout.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Riverside+Park,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Riverside Park</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="brooklyn" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Prospect_Park_(Brooklyn)"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted, Frederick Law + Vaux, Calvert</span><span class="entry-cost">1867</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Prospect Park</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Brooklyn</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">585 acres. Olmsted considered this their finest work, superior to Central Park. A continuous meadow, forest, and lake sequence without the cross-streets that interrupt Central Park's design. The Long Meadow is the longest open stretch of lawn in any urban park in the US.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Prospect+Park,+Brooklyn,+New+York" target="_blank">↗ Prospect Park</a>
</div>


<div class="entry" data-type="plaza" data-hood="lower-manhattan brooklyn" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Brooklyn_Bridge"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Roebling, John A. + Washington A. Roebling</span><span class="entry-cost">1883</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Brooklyn Bridge</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Lower Manhattan → DUMBO</span><span class="entry-tag">Infrastructure</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">1,595-foot main span. Steel wire suspension cables — the first large-scale use of steel wire rope in a bridge. John Roebling died before completion; his son Washington, partially paralyzed by caisson disease, supervised construction from a Brooklyn Heights window using binoculars, relaying instructions through his wife Emily. The pedestrian walkway above the vehicle lanes is one of the great urban promenades.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Brooklyn+Bridge,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Manhattan entrance: Park Row</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="plaza" data-hood="lower-manhattan brooklyn" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Manhattan_Bridge"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Carrère &amp; Hastings (towers) + Leon Moisseiff (engineering)</span><span class="entry-cost">1909</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Manhattan Bridge</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Canal St → DUMBO</span><span class="entry-tag">Infrastructure</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">The less-celebrated of the two East River suspension bridges. Viewed from the DUMBO pocket park on Washington Street — framed between the two bridge towers with the Brooklyn Bridge behind — it produces one of the most photographed urban compositions in the city. The upper level carries subway lines; the lower level carries traffic.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Manhattan+Bridge,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ DUMBO, Washington St viewpoint</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park" data-hood="uptown" data-arch="olmsted">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Central_Park"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Olmsted, Frederick Law + Vaux, Calvert</span><span class="entry-cost">1858</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Central Park</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Midtown → Upper Manhattan</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">843 acres. The original landscape design competition that established the American park movement. 36 bridges and arches, each unique. 58 miles of pedestrian paths, designed to separate foot, horse, and carriage traffic on four levels — the first application of grade separation to an urban park. The Ramble (36 acres of designed woodland) is the finest section.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Central+Park,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Central Park</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="plaza park" data-hood="west-village" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Little_Island"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Heatherwick Studio + MNLA (landscape)</span><span class="entry-cost">2021</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Little Island</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Pier 55, Hudson River Park</span><span class="entry-tag">Plaza + Infrastructure</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">2.4 acres on the Hudson River, resting on 132 tulip-shaped concrete pots on pilings driven into the riverbed. 350 species of plants across an undulating topography. Two performance spaces. Funded by Barry Diller and Diane von Fürstenberg. A notable counterpoint to Vessel — same architect, entirely opposite civic outcome. Free to enter.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Pier+55,+Hudson+River+Park,+New+York,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Pier 55, W 13th St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="park plaza" data-hood="brooklyn" data-arch="">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Brooklyn_Bridge_Park"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Michael Van Valkenburgh Associates</span><span class="entry-cost">2010–ongoing</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Brooklyn Bridge Park</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">DUMBO → Brooklyn Heights</span><span class="entry-tag">Park</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">85 acres of reclaimed industrial waterfront, 1.3 miles of East River shoreline. Six piers transformed from Port Authority cargo operations. Fill material salvaged from the Long Island Rail Road East Side Access project used to build topography. Salt marsh at Pier 1, urban beach at Pier 4. The relationship between private development within park boundaries and public space is the critical ongoing debate.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Brooklyn+Bridge+Park,+Brooklyn,+NY" target="_blank">↗ Pier 1 Entry, Old Fulton St</a>
</div>

