  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Lincoln, MA</span><span class="entry-tag">Residential</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Gropius's first American commission. Traditional New England post-and-beam frame combined with glass block, chrome banisters, and acoustic plaster. Interior original with Bauhaus furniture by Marcel Breuer and works by Albers, Miró, and Moore. Museum open Thursday–Sunday.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=68+Baker+Bridge+Rd,+Lincoln,+MA+01773" target="_blank">↗ 68 Baker Bridge Rd</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="residential" data-hood="mit" data-arch="holl">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Simmons_Hall_(MIT)"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Holl, Steven</span><span class="entry-cost">2002</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Simmons Hall</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">MIT Campus</span><span class="entry-tag">Residential</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Undergraduate dormitory organized as a porous sponge — Holl's explicit formal concept. 350 windows in a 10×10-foot grid. Five large voids penetrate the mass from ground to roof, providing light and cross-ventilation through the 350-foot-long block.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=229+Vassar+St,+Cambridge,+MA+02139" target="_blank">↗ 229 Vassar St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="boston" data-arch="kmc">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Boston_City_Hall"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Kallmann McKinnell &amp; Knowles</span><span class="entry-cost">1968</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Boston City Hall</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Government Center</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic + Academic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Won in a 1962 open design competition. Inverted ziggurat in board-formed béton brut: the building grows larger as it rises, council chambers and mayoral offices cantilevered over the open arcade. One of the canonical works of American Brutalism — consistently condemned by the public and defended by architects.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=1+City+Hall+Square,+Boston,+MA+02201" target="_blank">↗ 1 City Hall Square</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="tower" data-hood="boston" data-arch="pei">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="John_Hancock_Tower_(Boston)"><span>Add image</span></div>
