  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Columbia Point, Dorchester</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">16 years in design following the Kennedy assassination — community resistance to the original Cambridge site forced relocation to Columbia Point on Boston Harbor. A nine-story glass pavilion anchors a white concrete museum wing and cylindrical archive.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Columbia+Point,+Boston,+MA+02125" target="_blank">↗ Columbia Point</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="museum" data-hood="harvard" data-arch="piano">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Harvard_Art_Museums"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Piano, Renzo (RPBW)</span><span class="entry-cost">2014</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Harvard Art Museums Addition</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Harvard, Cambridge</span><span class="entry-tag">Museum</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Renovation and unification of three previously separate museums under a single glass roof forming a five-story interior courtyard. Piano preserved the 1927 Coolidge McKim Mead &amp; White Fogg courtyard facade as the interior's primary architectural element. The glass roof is a steel diagrid.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=32+Quincy+St,+Cambridge,+MA+02138" target="_blank">↗ 32 Quincy St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="boston" data-arch="rudolph">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Government_Service_Center_(Boston)"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Rudolph, Paul</span><span class="entry-cost">1971</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Government Services Center</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Government Center</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Rudolph's most ambitious urban project — a third-of-a-mile superblock intended as a spiraling megastructure anchored by a 23-story tower that was never built. Bush-hammered corduroy concrete. The unbuilt scheme remains legible in Rudolph's drawings.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Staniford+St,+Boston,+MA+02114" target="_blank">↗ Staniford St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="boston" data-arch="rudolph">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="First_Church_in_Boston"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Rudolph, Paul</span><span class="entry-cost">1972</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">First Church in Boston</h2>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">Back Bay</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">The 1867 church was largely destroyed by fire in 1968. Rudolph preserved the Roxbury puddingstone tower and east wall while constructing a new concrete nave — a complex of split-level platforms and voids organized around retained historic fabric.</p>
  <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=66+Marlborough+St,+Boston,+MA+02116" target="_blank">↗ 66 Marlborough St</a>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="mit" data-arch="saarinen">
  <div class="img-slot" data-wiki="Kresge_Auditorium"><span>Add image</span></div>
  <div class="entry-row"><span class="entry-label">Saarinen, Eero</span><span class="entry-cost">1955</span></div>
  <h2 class="entry-title">Kresge Auditorium + MIT Chapel</h2>
  <div class="icons"><span class="icon icon-landmark">Landmark</span></div>
  <p class="entry-meta"><span class="entry-tag">MIT Campus</span><span class="entry-tag">Civic + Academic</span></p>
  <p class="entry-blurb">Two buildings, two opposing formal strategies, same year. The auditorium is a thin concrete shell — one-eighth of a sphere — resting on three points. The Chapel is a windowless cylindrical brick drum in an artificial moat; light enters only from a single oculus above the altar, reflected off Bertoia's aluminum screen.</p>
  <div class="map-links">
    <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=Kresge+Auditorium,+MIT,+Cambridge,+MA" target="_blank">↗ Kresge</a>
    <a class="map-link" href="https://maps.google.com/?q=MIT+Chapel,+Cambridge,+MA" target="_blank">↗ Chapel</a>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="entry" data-type="civic" data-hood="boston" data-arch="sert">
